{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01XpdJ2NU3aZuHssHNY1jxRg","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see that `index.ts` has both `sql` (raw postgres) and `db` (the `Db` object from `createDb`). The closecall-clock currently only gets `sql`. I need to either:\n\n1. Pass `db` to the closecall-clock worker and use `db.insertUserTransaction()`\n2. Write raw SQL using the existing `sql` tagged template\n\nLooking at the pattern: the file already uses raw `sql` everywhere. The cleanest approach that's consistent with the checklist item is to write raw SQL using the existing `sql` tagged template. This avoids changing the deps interface and is consistent with how the rest of the file works.\n\n\nI realize now that other files like `settle-tx.ts` and `pda-watcher.ts` do use `db.insertUserTransaction()`, but they have their own separate postgres connection pools. Since the closecall-clock already has access to the `sql` template, I'll just write the raw insert statement directly with the conflict handling built in.\n\nNow I need to handle the transaction logging for each player. After the settlement update, I'll iterate through the green and red entries to record join events and outcomes. For payouts, winners split the pool minus fees based on their contribution, while losers and refunded players get their original amounts back. I have the entry data and refund flag ready to go.\n\nWriting transaction logging logic... Writing transaction logic... I need to be careful with the floating point math here—using `Math.floor((entry.amountLamports / sidePool) * netPool)` could introduce precision loss, but since these are lamports in the safe integer range and this is just a ledger entry rather than the actual payout, the standard JavaScript number math should work fine.\n\nNow I'm looking at how the `sql` tagged template works—it returns a `postgres.PendingQuery` that's thenable, and I can see the existing cod